<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="444" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1676,1880]" pageId="2" pageNumber="444">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,502,1748,1773]" pageId="2" pageNumber="444">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
The species is mostly associated with 
<taxonomicName box="[954,1010,1748,1773]" class="Ascidiacea" family="Polycitoridae" genus="Salix" kingdom="Animalia" order="Enterogona" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[954,1010,1748,1773]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="444">Salix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species but according to 
<bibRefCitation author="Moosavi" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" refString="Moosavi, N. &amp; Sadeghi Namaghi, H. (2012) Biodiversity of Auchenorrhyncha in sugar beet fields of Mashhad region and new records for Khorasan Razavi province. Journal of Sugar Beet, 28 (1), 7 - 12." type="journal article" year="2012">
Moosavi &amp; Sadeghi Namaghi 
<number box="[363,423,1784,1808]" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), the species has also been found on sugar beet. It is recorded from Europe to Northern Africa, 
<collectingCountry box="[240,285,1821,1844]" name="Iran" pageId="2" pageNumber="444">Iran</collectingCountry>
(North and Northeast, fig. 
<number box="[606,637,1820,1844]" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" value="21.0">21</number>
), Central and Northern Asia. The species is suggested as a potential vector for the bacterium 
<taxonomicName box="[428,568,1855,1880]" class="Gammaproteobacteria" family="Xanthomonadaceae" genus="Xylella" kingdom="Bacteria" order="Xanthomonadales" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" phylum="Proteobacteria" rank="species" species="fastidiosa">
<emphasis box="[428,568,1855,1880]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="444">X. fastidiosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which infests olive trees in Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="European" box="[984,1420,1855,1880]" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" refString="European Food Safety Authority (2013) Statement of EFSA on host plants, entry and spread pathways and risk reduction options for Xylella fastidiosa Wells et al. EFSA Journal, 11 (11), 3468, 50 pp." type="book" year="2013">
European Food Safety Authority 
<number box="[1359,1420,1856,1880]" pageId="2" pageNumber="444" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
